The Ar-180b utilizes the short stroke tappet operating system and while the rifle itself has faded it has cemented its legacy in modern firearms through the use of its operating system.  It should be noted that the AR18/180b bolt assembly has been adapted in more modern designed rifles such as the Heckler & Koch XM8 and G36 rifles as well as the British L85A1/SA80, FN SCAR, Magpul Massada/Bushmaster ACR and the Singaporean SAR-80/SAR-88. title: For Sale:  1941 Johnson Automatics
location: Bergen Cty, New Jersey, United States
postcontent: Three 1941 Johnsons for sale.  30-06.  Good "Starter Johnsons" since two are beautiful "Winfield Sporter" versions and one is military but slightly cracked stock.  See pic.$3,000 each, firm.Sporters: #1 (from the top) Really nice Winfield Sporter, deep blue on barrel and parts.  Has nice Redfield 4x on it and no front sight on the barrel.   Has some sporty carving in the wrist of the stock (which i think unattractive and would remove, but that's just me). #2 (from the top) has strong re-bluing and nicely refinished stock.   Looks closer to military save for the butt pad (which has hardened over the years) and the sporter front sight.   VERY nice example.#4 (the bottom one) is still in military configuration - more desirable for most collectors.  Finish on metal shows a lot of wear but everything functions fine - good shooter.   Light crack in the stock at the wrist - a very common thing for 19412 Johnsons.  Still functional stock though.  Interestingly, front sight with the wings filed off.  This is said to be a thing they did in the pacific theater to improve sight picture. And a shine to the stock, so must be refinished. But other wise all military. #3 not for sale - but I put it in there for comparison to a full original military (which unfortunately cost thousands more.Serious inquiries only, please.    Will ship, or can do FTF in NJ.SOME HISTORY:  After the United States entered the war in December 1941, demand for military arms soared. By this time, the Marine Corps had followed the Army's lead in adopting the M1 as its standard battle rifle, but M1 production was initially unable to meet demand. In addition, much to the Marine Corps' chagrin, the Army had first priority on available supplies and on future output from Springfield Armory and Winchester, the two manufacturers of the M1 Rifle. As a result, the Johnson M1941 rifle was adopted by the Marines for issue to Marine Raiders and to newly-formed Para-Marine airborne units (because the barrel could be removed for ease of jumping the weapon), and these rifles saw action in the Solomons campaign of 1942. As M1s became available to Marine units, the Johnson rifles were withdrawn from combat use. Only a few thousand of these arms had been procured by the U.S. government before production ended in 1944, and, in addition to their limited use with the Marine Corps, some Johnson rifles were issued to clandestine O.S.S. operatives. Because the rifle was never officially adopted by the US military, and because WWII prevented any opportunity Johnson may have had for robust foreign sales, the total number of Johnson 1941 Rifles manufactured was very small, only about 30,000. Johnson Model 1941 Rifles were serial numbered in groups of 10,000, with the first 10,000 having no prefix, the second group with prefix "A," third group with prefix "B."
